\section{Motivations and models description}
\label{sec:MotivModelDescription}
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

In this note, we want to describe the phenomenology of dark matter models involving a strong coupling to the top quark.
These models can be classified according to their flavour structure. When they are close the Standard Model flavour scheme, 
they essentially lead to $\ttbar + \met$ final state and are described in a separated document. Since we don't know the flavour structure
of the dark matter, it's interesting to relax this constraint leading to other experimental signatures: monotop final state 
and a prompt production of two top quarks having the same electric charge \textcolor{red}{Introduction do be modified since this is note quite correct}. 
These two final states have are forbiden at the leading order in the Standard Model and become thus a good area to search for any new physics, 
and in particular dark matter.

\subsection{Model structure}

The full details of the various models are described in \com{[ref]} but the basics ingredients are the following:
\begin{enumerate}
 \item the theory is effective but respects the $\SUtwoUone$ symmetry,
 \item the dark matter sector is coupled to SM fields via a mediator field which couple to the top quark,
 \item the top quark is \textit{singly} produced in association with a new particle $\Xnew$ (dark matter or mediator),
%  \item couplings should allow a visible $t\Xnew$ production rate in proton-proton collisions.
\end{enumerate}

There are 2 classes of model based on the monotop production mode: resonant and non-resonant production.

