\subsubsection{Non resonant production}

For the non-resonant production, the top quark is produced in association with the mediator 
($\Xnew$ is then the mediator and not the dark matter candidate). They are two possibilites 
depending on the nature of the mediator.

First, the mediator can be a scalar field interacting with the SM field and the dark matter candidate as described in this lagrangian:
\begin{equation}
 \label{eq:lagrangianNonResonantScalar}
 \Lagr_{\mathrm{int}} \; = \; g^{ij}_{\phi u} \: \bar{u}_{i} u_{j} \phi \; + \;  g_{\phi\chi} \: \bar{\chi}\chi \: \phi
\end{equation}
where the first term describe the interaction between the mediator and the $up$ quarks while the second term leads to the decay the mediator 
into invisible fermions. In this model, there is necessarily a mixing between $\phi$ and  the Higgs boson field. Additional parameters 
are then requiered to describe this new sector. Indeed, on top of the mediator mass and couplings, the mixing matix of the two scalar field
is needed in order to make predictions. For the sake of simplicity, we do not consider this case was the parameters 
space would be too large.

Another possibility is to consider a vectorial field as mediator with the following dymanics:
\begin{equation}
 \label{eq:lagrangianNonResonantVector}
 \Lagr_{\mathrm{int}} \; = \; g^{ij}_{Vu} \: \bar{u}_i \gam^{\mu} u_{j} \: V_{\mu} \; + \; g_{V\chi} \: \bar{\chi}\gam^{\mu} \chi \: V_{\mu}
\end{equation}
where the first term describe the interaction between the mediator and the $up$ quarks while the second term leads to the decay the mediator 
into invisible fermions. \com{Why it cannot mix with $\Zboson$ in case of vectorial mediator ?} The new sector can be defined 
with the couplings ($g^{ij}_{Vu}$, $g_{V\chi}$) and the masses $m_V$ and $m_{\chi}$. This model can be
probed by two experimental signatures depending on the exact scenario: monotop and same-sign top quark production. 

